text.text: Once home to Arsenal Football Club, Woolwich is now an oft forgotten, lost corner of London. We know there’s no such thing as a pocket of the Big Smoke completely devoid of intrigue though, and with the impending arrival of Crossrail, Woolwich is getting a bit of attention again. Some bits look sketchy on the surface (we did some scratching anyway), others seem a bit skeletal (the development is far from over)... LEZAVITLARGEWOOLWICH.
Best for… anything and everything (for your tum)

tip.text:
Koffees and Kream is much more than a pit stop, somewhere to grab a steaming cawfee on your way to some other place. No, this is that ‘some other place’ - a proper local eatery, good for all 3 daily meals, dishing up homemade, comfort nosh that ain’t looking to stretch them pockets too far.

We’re big fans of the decor in here, a quirky take on industrial interiors, while the menu is far from shabby - everything is made with fresh, locally sourced ingredients. Whether you’re after homemade pies, kalamari & chips (sic.), kebabs, steaks or a hearty Sunday roast, these are your guys. Bring your own choc or fruit and they’ll stick it in your shake. May have a whiff of ‘jack of all trades’ but that needn’t be the end of the world.

text.html: This diner does it all. Everything. Literally all of it. You’ve got your greasy-spoon breakfasts, your gastropub roasts, your bossman’s kebabs, your chippy’s fish 'n' chips (and much, much, much, much more) - all in one place. Plus all the ingredients are fresh and locally sourced. And every word on the menu that should start with a "c", is written with a "k". Kool.

tip.text:
Yes, a bona fide woods in London. We’re pretty sure it stops being acceptable to throw the term ‘London’ around just down the road from here, but benefits of finding yourself so far from the city include gorgeous, sweeping views of the home counties and proper countryside walk credentials. All of the above and you can still get there on a red bus.

Oxleas Wood features on the green chain walks, a network of footpaths linking up SE London’s open spaces.The cafe may not look like much but it’s a friendly hub for dog (and child) walkers and an apt stop-off for a refreshment - trust us, soaking in the vistas might leave you kind of parched.

text.html: Sometimes as a Londoner you forget that, y’know, there’s stuff outside of London. But there’s even stuff inside of London that feels (and looks) like it’s on the outside. Like Oxleas Wood: you’ll be afforded sweeping, green views of the counties beyond - and you’re only a bus ride away from the DLR. Stroll in the woods, swing on the swing suspended from a tree, get your trainers muddy mate. Then go to the cafe for a Ribena.

tip.text:
Modest on the outside, modest on the inside - but boy are people writing home about Blue Nile. In this family-run spot traditional Eritrean cuisine - curries packed with flavour and spice, served on freshly baked injera bread - coexists on a menu with Italian wines and lasagne specials: a nod to Eritrea’s colonial past.

So, what should you eat? Throw yourself in at the deep end and go for the meat and vegetable bebiaynetu; five delightful stews (three veg, two meat) on injera flatbread, with salad and yoghurt - get that between two of you and you’ll be well on your way to heaven. Hoza even makes her own Eritrean honey wine, and it’ll put a wobble in your step if you ain’t careful.

P.S. if you care about keepin' it real, don't ask for cutlery.

text.text: You don’t end up #1 on Tripadvisor's list of restaurants in London for no reason. Sure, be skeptical of the algorithm or the reviews and their authors, but it’s no coincidence: Blue Nile is hella dope! Proper Eritrean stews are going down in this kitchen daily and the flavours they’re packing are unreeeal. Lovely family-run joint in an old butcher’s shop: some of the original tiling remains, the rest went out the window (cough) when a tram flew into the shopfront some years back.
Best for... mind-blowing, tie-loosening, eye-popping views

tip.text:
We’d like to thank the people of Woolwich for their hard efforts campaigning to save and restore this wonderful structure - the council were ready to sell and the whole thing was boarded up and covered in graffiti. Now though, after years of crowdfunding and construction, Severndroog Castle stands proud, run exclusively by volunteers, and proves its worth as a phenomenal London attraction.

Believed to have been built by Lady James in memory of her late husband, Severndroog Castle is the highest public-access point between the City of London and Paris: the view from the top is something else completely - absolutely breathtaking stuff. Brownie points if you can name all seven counties observable from up there. Sandwiches, cakes and tea to be had in the downstairs Castlewood Tea Room.

Adults: £2.50
Children: £2.00
Families: £6.00

text.text: This is a proper gem and only a short stroll from Oxleas Wood. Severndroog Castle was built way back in 1784 - yes, we do our homework - and while it might not be the most sprawling of royal hangouts, there’s nowhere higher up between Paris and The City of London accessible to the public. That means views that will blow your socks, pants and undershirt off. Rescued by locals and run by volunteers, Severndroog Castle is a real treasure.
Best for… fancy pub grub and outdoor boozin’

tip.text:
They might’ve exposed the hell out of the brick in here (hello Shoreditch) but Youngs have actually set themselves up with a pretty nice gastropub in Royal Arsenal. The sheer size of this historic building, when smartly coupled with generous skylights, makes for a space that seems cosy and airy at the same time. Yes, you’ll be able to dip your toes in cask ales and wines, so don’t for a second think they’re short on liquids.

The menu aims to deliver fresh, seasonal British plates and pub classics alike - the roasted Dingley Dell pork belly sounds like a treat. With suppliers largely hailing from South East London, you can be confident that these lot know exactly what’s going on your plate. Great outdoor seating for sunny days.

text.html: The Royal Arsenal Riverside features some pretty awesome buildings - relics from its arms manufacturing past. Dial Arch is a colossus of brick and glass with a fine stretch of outdoor seating, suitable for super-sunny sangria sipping. Or, since this isn’t Spain, necking real ales in the lukewarm sun (which, let’s admit, is what dreams are made of). Inside? More brick, more glass, fine-ass gastro dining and plenty of cool furniture.

tip.text: Wondering how to get from Woolwich (Greenwich) to North Woolwich (Newham)? Look no further: this cool tunnel runs under the River Thames, takes less than 10 minutes to walk and, despite the “no cycling” signs, is full of lycra-clad push-bikers on the move. The lifts kind of smell like piss so bring a twig or something for pushing the buttons. Or take the stairs. Perfect spot to shoot that DIY music video of yours.

text.html: Admittedly, there aren’t a million reasons to check out Woolwich Foot Tunnel. There are a couple though. Sure, it’s a teeny weeny bit rank and stuff, but it is actually quite cool at the same time. The structures marking the entrance at either end are pretty epic and singular, while the eerie symmetry of the tunnel looks good in snaps and vids. Get your crew down here and shoot that ‘Blair Witch’ style music video - or just use it to walk under the Thames like everyone else.

tip.text:
Royal Arsenal’s only independent bar and restaurant, and proud. In an area booming with corporate development, it’s proper refreshing to find some cats flying their own flag: you’ll catch these good people at the Royal Arsenal Farmer’s Market showing off their beers (or buying seasonal ingredients for their pizzas!).

The goods that go on their pizzas are all fully fresh and locally sourced - and boy do the pizzas look good. Just for reference: the Sweet Italy features pears, gorgonzola and prosciutto ham (damn!). Don’t act like that’s not exciting. Beers come from small breweries only, and you can expect to see the likes of Hop Stuff (Arsenal’s own), Crate and Rooster’s on the taps in here. Wooden rafters and barrels make it well snug too.

text.html: Self-billed as the only independent bar and restaurant in Royal Arsenal, The Taproom are embracing their grassroots nature to the max. These good people are all about supporting small breweries and local growers, hence why you’ll likely catch them knocking about at the neighbourhood farmer’s market, either shopping for fresh pizza ingredients or showcasing the latest craft beers they’ve got in (when they’re not busy being open for business obvs).

tip.text:
Set in an old building society (built in 1935), there’s no small sense of grandeur about Antic’s first pub in Woolwich. That being said, inspired touches like vintage cinema seats and model ships add the right splash of character required to completely reinvent a space like this.

If you’re worried about the plumbing, don’t be. 6 real ale taps see the rotation of local and regional beers, including the elixirs of local microbrewery Hop Stuff, while bottled beers, wines and spirits feature also. The grub on offer is of the fresh and seasonal British variety (think prime cuts and fresh catches). Get down on Thursdays for the pub quiz or wile away your Sunday with board games and a roast.

text.html: Another day in Woolwich, another business in a really fucking cool building. This one’s an old building society, and now a pub by Antic - who’ve got some very decent ones around the capital with this one as a recent addition. Open spaces and random, quirky furniture make for a boozer with plenty of character, while you can absolutely expect a sound selection of dranks.
